   <h2>DICOM Code Definitions (DCM)</h2>
   <p>The meanings of codes defined in DICOM, either explicitly or by reference to another part
         of DICOM or an external reference document or standard</p>
   <p>These codes are excerpted from Digital Imaging and Communications in Medicine (DICOM)
         Standard, Part 16: Content Mapping Resource, Copyright 2011 by the National Electrical
         Manufacturers Association&quot;</p>
   <table>
      <tr>

      </tr>      
      <tr>
        <td><a name="109001">109001</a></td>
        <td>Digital timecode (NOS)</td>
        <td>A signal transmitted for the purpose of interchange of the current time, not specific
             to any source or methodology.</td>
      </tr>  
      <tr>
        <td><a name="109002">109002</a></td>
        <td>ECG-based gating signal, processed</td>
        <td>A signal which is generated for each detection of a heart beat</td>
      </tr>  
      <tr>
        <td><a name="109003">109003</a></td>
        <td>IRIG-B timecode</td>
        <td>A signal transmitted by the Inter-Range Instrumentation Group for the purpose of synchronizing
             time clocks.</td>
      </tr>  
      <tr>
        <td><a name="109004">109004</a></td>
        <td>X-Ray Fluoroscopy On Signal</td>
        <td>A signal which indicates that X-Ray source has been activated for fluoroscopy use.</td>
      </tr>  
      <tr>
        <td><a name="109005">109005</a></td>
        <td>X-Ray On Trigger</td>
        <td>A signal that indicated that the X-Ray source has been activated for image recording.</td>
      </tr>  
      <tr>

        <td>An electrical signal derived from two electrodes</td>
      </tr>

        <td><a name="110013">110013</a></td>

      <tr>
        <td><a name="110800">110800</a></td>
        <td>Spin Tagging Perfusion MR Signal Intensity</td>
        <td>Signal intensity of a Spin tagging Perfusion MR image. Spin tagging is a technique for
             the measurement of blood perfusion, based on magnetically labeled arterial blood water
             as an endogenous tracer.</td>
      </tr>  
      <tr>
        <td><a name="110801">110801</a></td>
        <td>Contrast Agent Angio MR Signal Intensity</td>
        <td>Signal intensity of a Contrast Agent Angio MR image.</td>
      </tr>  
      <tr>
        <td><a name="110802">110802</a></td>
        <td>Time Of Flight Angio MR Signal Intensity</td>
        <td>Signal intensity of a Time-of-flight (TOF) MR image. Time-of-flight (TOF) is based on
             the phenomenon of flow-related enhancement of spins entering into an imaging slice. As
             a result of being unsaturated, these spins give more signal that surrounding stationary
             spins.</td>
      </tr>  
      <tr>
        <td><a name="110803">110803</a></td>
        <td>Proton Density Weighted MR Signal Intensity</td>
        <td>Signal intensity of a Proton Density Weighted MR image. All MR images have intensity proportional
             to proton density. Images with very little T1 or T2 weighting are called ‘PD-weighted’.</td>
      </tr>  
      <tr>
        <td><a name="110804">110804</a></td>
        <td>T1 Weighted MR Signal Intensity</td>
        <td>Signal intensity of T1 Weighted MR image. A T1 Weighted MR image is created typically
             by using short TE and TR times.</td>
      </tr>  
      <tr>
        <td><a name="110805">110805</a></td>
        <td>T2 Weighted MR Signal Intensity</td>
        <td>Signal intensity of a T2 Weighted MR image. T2 Weighted image contrast state is approached
             by imaging with a TR long compared to tissue T1 (to reduce T1 contribution to image contrast)
             and a TE between the longest and shortest tissue T2s of interest.</td>
      </tr>  
      <tr>
        <td><a name="110806">110806</a></td>
        <td>T2* Weighted MR Signal Intensity</td>
        <td>Signal intensity of a T2* Weighted MR image. The T2* phenomenon results from molecular
             interactions (spin spin relaxation) and local magnetic field non-uniformities, which cause
             the protons to precess at slightly different frequencies.</td>
      </tr>  
      <tr>
        <td><a name="110807">110807</a></td>
        <td>Field Map MR Signal Intensity</td>
        <td>Signal intensity of a Field Map MR image. A Field Map MR image provides a direct measure
             of the B0 inhomogeneity at each point in the image.</td>
      </tr>  
      <tr>
        <td><a name="110808">110808</a></td>
        <td>Fractional Anisotropy</td>
        <td>Coefficient reflecting the fractional anisotropy of the tissues, derived from a diffusion
             weighted MR image. Fractional anisotropy is proportional to the square root of the variance
             of the Eigen values divided by the square root of the sum of the squares of the Eigen
             values.</td>
      </tr>  
      <tr>
        <td><a name="110809">110809</a></td>
        <td>Relative Anisotropy</td>
        <td>Coefficient reflecting the relative anisotropy of the tissues, derived from a diffusion
             weighted MR image.</td>
      </tr>  
      <tr>
        <td><a name="110810">110810</a></td>
        <td>Volumetric Diffusion Dxx Component</td>
        <td>Dxx Component of the diffusion tensor, quantifying the molecular mobility along the X
             axis.</td>
      </tr>  
      <tr>
        <td><a name="110811">110811</a></td>
        <td>Volumetric Diffusion Dxy Component</td>
        <td>Dxy Component of the diffusion tensor, quantifying the correlation of molecular displacements
             in the X and Y directions.</td>
      </tr>  
      <tr>
        <td><a name="110812">110812</a></td>
        <td>Volumetric Diffusion Dxz Component</td>
        <td>Dxz Component of the diffusion tensor, quantifying the correlation of molecular displacements
             in the X and Z directions.</td>
      </tr>  
      <tr>

             media from the blood pool into the extra vascular extracellular space (EES) of the brain

             in a spiral acquisition that is required for data interpolation).  Value is distinct from
             (1113825, DCM,”Scanning Length”), which is the actual length of the table travel during
             the entire tube loading, according to IEC 60601-2-44, and includes overranging. Also distinct
             from any actual Reconstructed Volume, which may depend on the slice thickness chosen for
             a particular reconstruction.</td>

        <td><a name="122322">122322</a></td>
        <td>Calibration Factor</td>
        <td>Factor by which a measured or calculated value is multiplied to obtain the estimated real-world
             value.</td>
      </tr>  
      <tr>
        <td><a name="122325">122325</a></td>
        <td>IVUS Report</td>
        <td>Intravascular Ultrasound Report</td>
      </tr>  
      <tr>
        <td><a name="122330">122330</a></td>
        <td>EEM Diameter</td>
        <td>External Elastic Membrane (EEM) diameter measured through the center point of the vessel.
             Center point of the vessel is defined as the center of gravity of the EEM area. The EEM
             is a discrete interface at the border between the media and the adventitia.</td>
      </tr>  
      <tr>
        <td><a name="122331">122331</a></td>
        <td>Plaque Plus Media Thickness</td>
        <td>The distance from intimal leading edge to the external elastic membrane along any line
             passing through the luminal center, which is defined as the center of gravity of the lumen
             area.</td>
      </tr>  
      <tr>
        <td><a name="122332">122332</a></td>
        <td>Lumen Perimeter</td>
        <td>Planimetered perimeter of the lumen.</td>
      </tr>  
      <tr>
        <td><a name="122333">122333</a></td>
        <td>EEM Cross-Sectional Area</td>
        <td>Vessel area measured at the External Elastic Membrane (EEM), a discrete interface at the
             border between the media and the adventitia.</td>
      </tr>  
      <tr>
        <td><a name="122334">122334</a></td>
        <td>Plaque plus Media Cross-Sectional Area</td>
        <td>Area within the EEM occupied by atheroma, regardless of lumen compromise. Plaque plus
             Media Area = EEM cross-sectional area - vessel lumen cross-sectional area</td>
      </tr>  
      <tr>
        <td><a name="122335">122335</a></td>
        <td>In-Stent Neointimal Cross-Sectional Area</td>
        <td>Measurement of in-stent restenosis. In-Stent Intimal Area = Stent cross-sectional area
             – vessel lumen cross-sectional area</td>
      </tr>  
      <tr>
        <td><a name="122336">122336</a></td>
        <td>Vascular Volume measurement length</td>
        <td>Longitudinal extent of the Vascular Volume Measurement. This is the distance from the
             distal edge to the proximal edge of the Volume measurement.</td>
      </tr>  
      <tr>
        <td><a name="122337">122337</a></td>
        <td>Relative position</td>
        <td>Longitudinal distance from the closest edge of a fiducial feature or reference location
             to the start of the vascular measurement. This value will be a positive if the measurement
             is distal to the fiducial feature or reference location, or negative if the measurement
             is proximal to the fiducial feature or reference location.</td>
      </tr>  
      <tr>
        <td><a name="122339">122339</a></td>
        <td>Stent Volume Obstruction</td>
        <td>In-Stent Neointimal Volume / Stent Volume</td>
      </tr>  
      <tr>
        <td><a name="122340">122340</a></td>
        <td>Fiducial feature</td>
        <td>Reference, normally anatomical, which is used for locating the position of a measurement.</td>
      </tr>  
      <tr>
        <td><a name="122341">122341</a></td>
        <td>Calcium Length</td>
        <td>Longitudinal calcium length measurement</td>
      </tr>  
      <tr>
        <td><a name="122343">122343</a></td>
        <td>Lumen Eccentricity Index</td>
        <td>Measurement of vessel lumen eccentricity. Lumen Eccentricity Index = (maximum vessel lumen
             diameter - minimum vessel lumen diameter) / maximum vessel lumen diameter. Lumen diameters
             are measured through the center point of the lumen, which is defined as the center of
             gravity of the lumen area.</td>
      </tr>  
      <tr>
        <td><a name="122344">122344</a></td>
        <td>Plaque plus Media Eccentricity Index</td>
        <td>Plaque plus Media Eccentricity Index  = (maximum Plaque plus media thickness - minimum
             Plaque plus media thickness) / maximum Plaque plus media thickness</td>
      </tr>  
      <tr>
        <td><a name="122345">122345</a></td>
        <td>Remodeling Index</td>
        <td>Measurement of increase or decrease in EEM area that occurs during the development of
             atherosclerosis. Remodeling Index = Lesion EEM area / reference EEM area</td>
      </tr>  
      <tr>
        <td><a name="122346">122346</a></td>
        <td>Stent Symmetry Index</td>
        <td>Measurement of stent circularity. Stent Symmetry Index = (maximum stent diameter - minimum
             stent diameter) / maximum stent diameter</td>
      </tr>  
      <tr>
        <td><a name="122347">122347</a></td>
        <td>Stent Expansion Index</td>
        <td>Measurement of stent area relative to the reference lumen area. Stent Expansion Index
             = Minimum stent area / reference vessel lumen cross-sectional area</td>
      </tr>  
      <tr>
        <td><a name="122348">122348</a></td>
        <td>Lumen Shape Index</td>
        <td>Measurement of vessel lumen eccentricity. Lumen Shape Index = (2p * sqrt(Vessel lumen
             cross-sectional area / p) / Lumen Perimeter) 2  Reference: Tobis &amp; Yock, “Intravascular
             Ultrasound Imaging”,  Chapter 7</td>
      </tr>  
      <tr>
        <td><a name="122350">122350</a></td>
        <td>Lumen Diameter Ratio</td>
        <td>Lumen diameter ratio = minimum vessel lumen diameter / maximum vessel lumen diameter,
             measured at the same cross section in the vessel. Lumen diameters are measured through
             the center point of the lumen, which is defined as the center of gravity of the lumen
             area.</td>
      </tr>  
      <tr>
        <td><a name="122351">122351</a></td>
        <td>Stent Diameter Ratio</td>
        <td>Stent diameter ratio = Minimum stent diameter / Maximum stent diameter, measured at the
             same cross section in the vessel. Stent diameters are measured through the center point
             of the stent, which is defined as the center of gravity of the stent area.</td>
      </tr>  
      <tr>
        <td><a name="122352">122352</a></td>
        <td>EEM Diameter Ratio</td>
        <td>EEM diameter ratio = minimum EEM diameter / maximum EEM diameter. Measured at the same
             cross section in the vessel.</td>
      </tr>  
      <tr>
        <td><a name="122354">122354</a></td>
        <td>Plaque Burden</td>
        <td>Fractional area within the External Elastic Membrane (EEM) occupied by atheroma. Plaque
             Burden  = (EEM area - vessel lumen cross-sectional area) / EEM area</td>
      </tr>  
      <tr>
        <td><a name="122355">122355</a></td>
        <td>Arc of Calcium</td>
        <td>Angular measurement of a Calcium deposit with the apex located at the center of the lumen,
             which is defined as the center of gravity of the lumen area.</td>
      </tr>  
      <tr>

            tent Neointimal Volume  = Stent Volume - Lumen Volume</td>

      <tr>
        <td><a name="122375">122375</a></td>

             Total Plaque Volume = EEM Volume - Lumen Volume.</td>

             proximal to a stenosis but within the same segment (usually within 10 mm of the stenosis
             with no major intervening branches).</td>

      <tr>
        <td><a name="122394">122394</a></td>
        <td>Fibro-Lipidic Plaque</td>
        <td>Loosely packed bundles of collagen fibers with regions of lipid deposition present. Region
             is cellular and no cholesterol clefts or necrosis are present. Some macrophage infiltration.
             Increase in extra cellular matrix.</td>
      </tr>  
      <tr>
        <td><a name="122395">122395</a></td>
        <td>Necrotic-Lipidic Plaque</td>
        <td>Area within the plaque with very low echogenicity separated from the lumen and surrounded
             by more echogenic structures (fibrous cap). Highly lipidic necrotic region with remnants
             of foam cells and dead lymphocytes present. No collagen fibers are visible and mechanical
             integrity is poor.  Cholesterol clefts and micro calcifications are visible.</td>
       </tr>
      <tr>
        <td><a name="122398">122398</a></td>

      </tr>  
      <tr>
        <td><a name="122466">122466</a></td>
        <td>Single LAD Region in RAO Projection</td>
        <td>Based on a total number of chords of 100 and RAO projection the range of chords belonging
             to this regional extent lies between 10 – 66 (hypokinetic) and 67 – 80 (hyperkinetic).

             domain. Includes Low Pass, High Pass, Gaussian, Laplacian, etc.</td>
      </tr>

        <td>Adaptive Filtering</td>
        <td>Surface processing applied non-uniformly utilizing a priori knowledge of the system and/or
             relative locations of the data values within the data domain. Example: Neighborhood analysis
             where weighting factors are modified continuously based on predefined criteria.</td>
      </tr>  
      <tr>
        <td><a name="123103">123103</a></td>
        <td>Edge Detection</td>

             their domain. Includes Gradient filters.</td>
      </tr>  
      <tr>
        <td><a name="123104">123104</a></td>
        <td>Morphological Operations</td>
        <td>Surface processing based on the connectivity of values based on the shape or structure
             of the data values within their domain. Includes erode, dilate, etc.</td>
      </tr>  
      <tr>
        <td><a name="123105">123105</a></td>
        <td>Histogram Analysis</td>

             Bayesian Classification, etc.</td>
      </tr>  
      <tr>
        <td><a name="123106">123106</a></td>
        <td>Multi-Scale/Resolution Filtering</td>
        <td>Surface processing accomplished through varying the data domain size. Include deformable
             models.</td>
      </tr>  
      <tr>
        <td><a name="123107">123107</a></td>
        <td>Cluster Analysis</td>
        <td>Surface processing accomplished by combining data values based on their relative location
             within their domain or value distribution. Includes K- and C-means, Fuzzy Analysis, Watershed,
             Seed Growing, etc.</td>
      </tr>  
      <tr>
        <td><a name="123108">123108</a></td>
        <td>Multispectral Processing</td>
        <td>Surface processing accomplished through the weighted combination of multiple data sets.
             Includes Principle Component Analysis, linear and non-linear weighed combinations, etc.</td>
      </tr>  
      <tr>
        <td><a name="123109">123109</a></td>
        <td>Manual Processing</td>
        <td>Surface processing accomplished through human interaction. Region drawing</td>
      </tr>  
      <tr>

             Acquisition protocols may be specific to a manufacturer’s product.</td>

      <tr>
        <td><a name="125204">125204</a></td>
        <td>Area-length biplane</td>
        <td>Method for calculating left ventricular volume from two orthogonal views containing the
             true long axis (usually the apical 4 and 2 chamber views). Volume = [p L1/6]*[(4A1)¸(pL1)]*[(4A2)¸(p
             L2)]</td>
      </tr>  
      <tr>
        <td><a name="125205">125205</a></td>
        <td>Area-Length Single Plane</td>
        <td>Method for calculating left ventricular volume from a view containing the true long axis
             (usually the apical 4-chamber view). Volume = [8(A)2]¸[3pL]</td>
      </tr>  
      <tr>
        <td><a name="125206">125206</a></td>
        <td>Cube</td>
        <td>Method (formula) for calculating left ventricle volumes and function derivatives (EF,
             SV, SI, etc.) that estimates the volume as the cube of diameter.</td>
      </tr>  
      <tr>
        <td><a name="125207">125207</a></td>
        <td>Method of Disks, Biplane</td>
        <td>Method of calculating volume based on the summation of disk volumes. The disk axis is
             parallel to the left ventricular long axis and using a disk diameter averaged from the
             two chamber and four chamber views.</td>
      </tr>  
      <tr>
        <td><a name="125208">125208</a></td>
        <td>Method of Disks, Single Plane</td>
        <td>Method of calculating volume based on the summation of disk volumes. The disk axis is
             parallel to the left ventricular long axis with disk diameter taken from the four-chamber
             view.</td>
      </tr>  
      <tr>
        <td><a name="125209">125209</a></td>
        <td>Teichholz</td>
        <td>Method (formula) for calculating left ventricle volumes and function derivatives (EF,
             SV, SI, etc.) Volume = [7.0/(2.4+D)]*D3</td>
      </tr>  
      <tr>
        <td><a name="125210">125210</a></td>
        <td>Area by Pressure Half-Time</td>
        <td>Mitral valve area (cm2) by Pressure Half-time = 220 (cm2.ms) / PHT (ms)</td>
      </tr>  
      <tr>
        <td><a name="125211">125211</a></td>
        <td>Biplane Ellipse</td>
        <td>Area = P/4 X d1 X d2 d1 = anterior/posterior axis d2 = medial/lateral axis Hagen-Ansert,
             Sandra L., Textbook of Diagnostic Ultrasound, ed. 3, The C.V.Mosby Co., 1989, p. 73.</td>
      </tr>  
      <tr>
        <td><a name="125212">125212</a></td>
        <td>Continuity Equation</td>
        <td>For conduits in series (“in continuity”), volume flow is equal: A1*V1 = A2*V2. where V
             is the velocity</td>
      </tr>  
      <tr>
        <td><a name="125213">125213</a></td>
        <td>Continuity Equation by Mean Velocity</td>
        <td>For conduits in series (“in continuity”), volume flow is equal: A1*V1 = A2*V2. where V
             is the mean velocity</td>
      </tr>  
      <tr>
        <td><a name="125214">125214</a></td>
        <td>Continuity Equation by Peak Velocity</td>
        <td>For conduits in series (“in continuity”), volume flow is equal: A1*V1 = A2*V2. where V
             is the peak velocity</td>
      </tr>  
      <tr>
        <td><a name="125215">125215</a></td>
        <td>Continuity Equation by Velocity Time Integral</td>
        <td>For conduits in series (“in continuity”), volume flow is equal: A1*V1 = A2*V2. where V
             is the velocity time integral</td>
      </tr>  
      <tr>
        <td><a name="125216">125216</a></td>
        <td>Proximal Isovelocity Surface Area</td>
        <td>Utilizes aliasing velocity (by color Doppler) of flow into an orifice (often regurgitant
             or stenotic) to measure instantaneous flow rate, orifice area, and flow volume. The instantaneous
             flow rate = (2 π r2 vav ) * (α / π) where vav  is the constant velocity known as aliasing
             velocity at radius r, vp is the peak velocity at the orifice, and α is the angle in radians
             of the constant velocity surface. Estimated Orifice area = Flow rate / vp, where vp is
             the peak velocity at the orifice and the flow rate is the PISA peak flow rate. The volume
             flow is then the product of the orifice area and Velocity Time Integral</td>
      </tr>  
      <tr>
        <td><a name="125217">125217</a></td>
        <td>Full Bernoulli</td>
        <td>ΔP = 4*(V12 – V22)</td>
      </tr>  
      <tr>
        <td><a name="125218">125218</a></td>
        <td>Simplified Bernoulli</td>
        <td>ΔP = 4*V2</td>
      </tr>  
      <tr>
        <td><a name="125219">125219</a></td>
        <td>Doppler Volume Flow</td>
        <td>Volume flow = Conduit CSA * ( Velocity Time Integral )</td>
      </tr>  
      <tr>
        <td><a name="125220">125220</a></td>

        <td>Direct measurement of an area by tracing an irregular perimeter</td>
      </tr>  
      <tr>
        <td><a name="125221">125221</a></td>
        <td>Left Ventricle Mass by M-mode</td>
        <td>Mass = 1.04 * [(ST+LVID+PWT)3-LVID3] * 0.8+ 0.6. Mass unit is grams and length in cm.</td>
      </tr>  
      <tr>
        <td><a name="125222">125222</a></td>
        <td>Left Ventricle Mass by Truncated Ellipse</td>
        <td>Mass =  1.05 P ( (b + t)2 X (2/3 (a + t) + d – d3/3(a + t)2 ) – b2 (2/3a + d – d3/3a2)
             ) a = Semi-major axis from widest minor axis radius to apex. b = Short axis radius calculated
             from short axis cavity area t = Myocardial thickness calculated from short axis epicardial
             and cavity areas d = Truncated semi-major axis from widest short axis diameter to plane
             of mitral annulus. Mass unit is grams and length in cm. Schiller NB et al: Recommendations
             for quantification of the left ventricle by two-dimensional echocardiography, American
             Society of Echocardiography 2:364, 1989.</td>
      </tr>  
      <tr>
        <td><a name="125223">125223</a></td>
        <td>4 Point Segment Finding Scale</td>

             evaluation of wall motion and ventricle morphology. Recommendations for Quantitation of
             the Left Ventricle by Two-Dimensional Echocardiography, Journal of the American Society
             of Echocardiography, 2:358-367, 1989.</td>
      </tr>

             Recommendations for Quantitation of the Left Ventricle by Two-Dimensional Echocardiography,
             Journal of the American Society of Echocardiography, 2:358-367, 1989.</td>

        <td>Modified Simpson</td>
        <td>Modified Simpson’s Method of estimating ventricular volume, based on the method of disks
             with paired apical views. Schiller NB, et al. “Recommendations for quantitation of the
             left ventricle by two-dimensional echocardiography. American Society of Echocardiography
             Committee on Standards, Subcommittee on Quantitation of Two-Dimensional Echocardiograms”.
             J Am Soc Echocardiogr. 1989 2(5):358-367. Sep-Oct.</td>
      </tr>

        <td><a name="125228">125228</a></td>
        <td>Bullet Method</td>

      <tr>
        <td><a name="125270">125270</a></td>
        <td>Left Ventricle Mass by Area Length</td>
        <td>method to measure the mass of the Left Ventricle via the ASE area-length method at end
             diastole. LV Mass = 1.05*(5/6*(A1*(L+t) ) - 5/6*(A2*L) ) A1 = Left Ventricle epicardial
             SAX area at the level of of the papillary muscle tips at end diastole. A2 = Left Ventricle
             endocardial SAX area cavity area at the level of the papillary muscle tips at end diastole.
             L = Left Ventricle apical view long axis length at end diastole. t = Myocardial thickness
             can be computed as :  t = sqrt( A1/3.14) – sqrt ( A2/3.14) Reference: 1) Schiller, N.B.,
             et al. “Recommendations for Quantification of the LV by Two-dimensional Echocardiography.&quot;
             J Am Soc Echo, Vol. 2, No. 5: 358-367, Sep-Oct 1989. 2) Reichek, N., et al. &quot;Anatomic
             Validation of Left Ventricular Mass Estimates from Clinical Two-dimensional Echocardiography:
             Initial Results.&quot; Circulation, Vol. 67, No. 2: 348-52, February 1983.</td>
      </tr>  
      <tr>
        <td><a name="125271">125271</a></td>
        <td>Left Ventricle Mass by M-mode – adjusted by Height</td>
        <td>Equation = Left Ventricle Mass by M-mode (in gram) / ( Height (in meter) )^2.7 Reference:
             Giovanni De Simone, et al. “Effect of Growth on Variability of Left Ventricular Mass:
             Assessment of Allometric Signals in Adults and Children and Their Capacity to Predict
             Cardiovascular Risk”. New York, New York and Cincinnati, Ohio.</td>
      </tr>  
      <tr>
        <td><a name="125272">125272</a></td>
        <td>Left Ventricle Mass by Truncated Ellipse – adjusted by Height</td>
        <td>Equation = Left Ventricle Mass by Truncated Ellipse / Height^2.7 Reference: Giovanni De
             Simone, et al. “Effect of Growth on Variability of Left Ventricular Mass: Assessment of
             Allometric Signals in Adults and Children and Their Capacity to Predict Cardiovascular
             Risk”. New York, New York and Cincinnati, Ohio.</td>
      </tr>  
      <tr>
        <td><a name="125273">125273</a></td>
        <td>Left Ventricle Mass by Area Length – adjusted by Height</td>
        <td>Equation = Left Ventricle Mass by Area Length / Height^2.7 Reference: Giovanni De Simone,
             et al. “Effect of Growth on Variability of Left Ventricular Mass: Assessment of Allometric
             Signals in Adults and Children and Their Capacity to Predict Cardiovascular Risk”. New
             York, New York and Cincinnati, Ohio.</td>
      </tr>

  <name value="DICOM Code Definitions (DCM)"/>
  <publisher value="NEMA/DICOM"/>
  <description value="The meanings of codes defined in DICOM, either explicitly or by reference to another part
   of DICOM or an external reference document or standard (OID = 1.2.840.10008.2.16.4)"/>
  <copyright value="These codes are excerpted from Digital Imaging and Communications in Medicine (DICOM)
   Standard, Part 16: Content Mapping Resource, Copyright 2011 by the National Electrical
   Manufacturers Association"/>
  <status value="active"/>
  <date value="2010-08-26"/>
  <define>
    <system value="http://nema.org/dicom/dcid"/>
    <caseSensitive value="true"/>

    <concept>
      <code value="109001"/>
      <display value="Digital timecode (NOS)"/>
      <definition value="A signal transmitted for the purpose of interchange of the current time, not specific
       to any source or methodology."/>
    </concept>  
    <concept>
      <code value="109002"/>
      <display value="ECG-based gating signal, processed"/>
      <definition value="A signal which is generated for each detection of a heart beat"/>
    </concept>  
    <concept>
      <code value="109003"/>
      <display value="IRIG-B timecode"/>
      <definition value="A signal transmitted by the Inter-Range Instrumentation Group for the purpose of synchronizing
       time clocks."/>
    </concept>  
    <concept>
      <code value="109004"/>
      <display value="X-Ray Fluoroscopy On Signal"/>
      <definition value="A signal which indicates that X-Ray source has been activated for fluoroscopy use."/>
    </concept>  
    <concept>
      <code value="109005"/>
      <display value="X-Ray On Trigger"/>
      <definition value="A signal that indicated that the X-Ray source has been activated for image recording."/>
    </concept>  
    <concept>
      <code value="109006"/>
      <display value="Differential signal"/>
      <definition value="An electrical signal derived from two electrodes"/>
    </concept>  
    <concept>
      <code value="109007"/>
      <display value="His bundle electrogram"/>
      <definition value="An electrophysiological recording from the HIS nerve bundle"/>
    </concept>  
    <concept>
      <code value="109008"/>
      <display value="Monopole signal"/>
      <definition value="An electrical signal from one electrode relative to an indifferent potential."/>
    </concept>  
    <concept>
      <code value="109009"/>
      <display value="Pacing (electrical) stimulus, voltage"/>
      <definition value="The voltage stimulus during cardiac pacing"/>
    </concept>  
    <concept>

    <concept>
      <code value="125216"/>
      <display value="Proximal Isovelocity Surface Area"/>
      <definition value="Utilizes aliasing velocity (by color Doppler) of flow into an orifice (often regurgitant
       or stenotic) to measure instantaneous flow rate, orifice area, and flow volume. The instantaneous
       flow rate = (2 π r2 vav ) * (α / π) where vav  is the constant velocity known as aliasing
       velocity at radius r, vp is the peak velocity at the orifice, and α is the angle in radians
       of the constant velocity surface. Estimated Orifice area = Flow rate / vp, where vp is
       the peak velocity at the orifice and the flow rate is the PISA peak flow rate. The volume
       flow is then the product of the orifice area and Velocity Time Integral"/>

       from short axis cavity area t = Myocardial thickness calculated from short axis epicardial
       and cavity areas d = Truncated semi-major axis from widest short axis diameter to plane
       of mitral annulus. Mass unit is grams and length in cm. Schiller NB et al: Recommendations

       et al. “Recommendations for Quantification of the LV by Two-dimensional Echocardiography.&quot;
       J Am Soc Echo, Vol. 2, No. 5: 358-367, Sep-Oct 1989. 2) Reichek, N., et al. &quot;Anatomic
